narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: It's an excellent class, and I would recommend it to any student because the readings are excellent and the format of the class is very engaging.

English 127 exposed me to pieces of American literature that I hadn't had the chance to read during high school, which I value (reading Moby Dick was a challenging way to start off the year, but was a very rewarding read). The course moves quickly,oftentimes covering a work in just a week. I also felt that the course helped me to improve my analytical writing skills.

This class is a great overview of some of the major texts in the American canon. The books are interesting, and the workload is manageable. I definitely suggest it. The classes were very engaging and interesting.

This was a great course. There was a lot of reading, which could make a hard semester even harder, but the reading was great, for the most part, and the in-class discussions were even better. I think the readings could be evened out a bit more, to prevent some days from having 200 pgs due. The final exam could also benefit from a slight restructuring: due to the intense time pressure, the essays on the final exam end up being poorly written--and they are written very differently from the ways of writing we develop during the course. The course was very challenging, but also very rewarding.

A great intro to American literature. While it is reading intensive, it is very rewarding with great feedback on writing and the historical context of the readings. I would recommend researching the historical context of the readings before class and maybe even before doing the reading. Professor Cecire rocks; she is very approachable and takes the time to prepare helpful supplementary class materials as well as provide constructive feedback on essays.
